    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Call of Nature</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Deborah Grace Winer letter responds to Jesse McKinley article on reflexive Broadway shows (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Broadway's Favorite Subject: Itself'' by Jesse McKinley [April 13]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Broadway's Favorite Subject: Itself'' by Jesse McKinley [April 13]:</p>
        <p>I amiably take issue with the premise that there are so many shows about show business simply because Broadway is stuck on itself. (Though of course it is.) The tradition stems more from the fact that the ''Hey kids, let's put on a show'' call of nature is as primal to humans as sleeping or eating sweets.</p>
        <p>The perceived glamour and backstage tribulations of show business haven't fascinated just Broadway. The ancients, Shakespeare, commedia dell'arte and seven decades of Hollywood movies all beckon to a public with stars in its eyes and a yen for self-expression.</p>
        <p>The proof? There's school play fever. And the fact that every 30 seconds, somewhere in the world another pinstriped professional is crooning ''Misty'' into a karaoke machine. And ''American Idol.''</p>
        <p>DEBORAH GRACE WINER  Manhattan</p>
        <p>ON BROADWAY</p>
      </block>
